<h2>To John Hancock</h2>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Cambridge February the 14. 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Through you I beg leave to lay before Congress, the Inclosed Letter from Lord Drummond to General Robertson, which came to my hands a few days agoe in order to be sent into Boston.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>As I never heard of his Lor[d]ship being vested with power to treat with Congress upon the Subject of our Greivances nor of his having laid any propositions before them for an Accomodation, I confess It surprized me much, and led me to form various conjectures of his motives, and Intended application to General Howe &amp; Admiral Shouldam for a pasport for the safe Conduct of such Deputies as Congress might appoint for Negociating Terms of Reconciliation between Great Britain and us. Whatever his Intentions are, however benevolent his designs may be, I confess that his Letter has embarrassed me much, and I am not without suspicion of Its meaning more than the Generous purposes It professes. I should suppose that If the mode for Negociation which he points out, should be adopted, which I hope will never be thought of, that It ought to have been fixed and settled previous to any application of this sort, and at best that his conduct in this Instance is premature and Officious, &amp; leading to consequences of a fatal and Injurious nature to the rights of this Country. his zeal and desire perhaps of an amicable &amp; constitutional adjustments taking place may have Suggested &amp; precipitated the measure, be that as It may, I thought It of too much importance to suffer It to go in without having the express direction of Congress for that purpose, and
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0307">[307]</span>
that It was my Indispensable duty to transmit them the Original to make such Interpretations and Inferences as they may think right.</p>
<p>Messrs Willard &amp; Child who were sent to Nova Scotia in pursuance of the Resolve of Congress, have just returned and made their Report, which I do myself the honor to Inclose you. they have not Answered the purposes of their commission by any means, as they only went but a little way into that Country, and found their Intelligence upon the Information of Others. You will see the reasons they Assign in excuse or justification of their conduct in the Report Itself.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>Last night a party of Regulars, said to be about Five hundred, landed on Dorchester Neck and burnt some of the Houses there, which were of no value to us, nor would they have been, Unless we take post there; they then might have been of some service. A Detachment went after them as soon as the fire was discovered, but before It could arrive, they had executed their plan and made their retreat.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>Inclosed is a Letter for David Franks Esqr. from Mr Chamier in Boston, upon the Subject of victualling such of the Kings Troops as may be prisoners within the Limits of his Contract, which I beg the favour of you to deliver him, and that proper agents may be appointed by him to see that It is doneI could wish too that Congress would fall upon some mode for Supplying the Officers with such Money as they may really stand in need of, and depute proper persons for that purpose &amp; furnishing the privates with such Cloathing as may be absolutely necessary; I am applied to and wearied by their repeated requestsIn some Instances I have desired the Committees to give the prisoners within their appointments, what they should Judge absolutely necessary for their support, as the only means in my power of releiving their distressBut I immagine that If there were persons to superintend this business, that their wants would be better attended to, and many exorbitant charges prevented and saved to the Continent &amp; the whole woud then be brought into a proper account.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> I am Sir with great esteem &amp; regard Your Most Hble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>P.S. I send a Return of the strength of the Regiments.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0005-ptr">5</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0308">[308]</span>
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Signed: a letter not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author ]">LS</abbr>, in Robert Hanson Harrisons writing, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Papers of the Continental Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA:PCC</span>, item 152; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; 
copy, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Papers of the Continental Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA:PCC</span>, item 169; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 Congress read this letter on 29 Feb. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:178).</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>For the text of Lord Drummonds letter to Brig. Gen. James Robertson of 5 Feb. 1776, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0185&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0185-fn-0002#GEWN-03-03-02-0185-fn-0002" class="document">Thomas Lynch to GW, that date, n.2</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The report of Aaron Willard and Moses Child is printed as an enclosure to this letter. For the appointment of these two men and their instructions, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0317&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-02-02-0317-fn-0001#GEWN-03-02-02-0317-fn-0001" class="document">Hancock to GW, 10 Nov., n.1</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0367" class="document">GW to Hancock, 19 Nov</a>., <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0386" class="document">GW to a Committee of the Massachusetts Council, 24 Nov</a>., and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0388" class="document">GWs instructions to Willard and Child, 24 Nov. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>At 4 oclock this morning a British detachment of 400 men, consisting of 6 companies of light infantry and 6 companies of grenadiers, crossed the ice from Boston Neck to Nooks Hill on the eastern end of Dorchester Neck. About the same time 400 men of the British 64th Regiment left Castle William and landed at the western end of the neck. Faced with these superior forces, the commander of the American guard on Dorchester Neck, Capt. Daniel Barnes, retreated with most of his sixty men before they could be cut off, and called for reinforcements. The two British raiding parties then moved across the neck unopposed, burning six to eight unoccupied houses and barns and capturing six straggling guards and an elderly inhabitant. The British returned to their lines about 6:30 in the morning just as the American reinforcements were coming up. See <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Harry Miller Lydenberg, ed. &lt;i&gt;Archibald Robertson, Lieutenant-General Royal Engineers: His Diaries and Sketches in America, 17621780&lt;/i&gt;. New York, 1930. ]">Lydenberg, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Robertson Diaries</span></span>, 72, <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Frank Moore. &lt;i&gt;Diary of the American Revolution from Newspapers and Original Documents&lt;/i&gt;. 2 vols. New York, 185960. ]">Moore, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diary</span></span>, 1:2056, and <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Danske Dandridge. &lt;i&gt;Historic Shepherdstown&lt;/i&gt;. Charlottesville, Va., 1910. ]">Dandridge, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Shepherdstown</span></span>, 126.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>The enclosed letter from Daniel Chamier, commissary general of the British army at Boston, to David Franks, commissary for the British prisoners in Pennsylvania, has not been identified. For GWs earlier request for the appointment of a commissary for all British prisoners, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0200" class="document">GW to Hancock, 9 Feb. 1776 (third letter)</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0222-0001-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>This enclosure may be the General Return of the Army of the United Colonies dated 4 Feb. 1776 in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA</span>: <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Record Group (designating the location of documents in the National Archives) ]">RG</span> 93, Revolutionary War Rolls, 177583.</p>

</div>
